AGI -&nbsp;The Turkish Authority for Communications (RTUK) has sanctioned four television broadcasters >&nbsp; bound to the opposition, ended in the viewpoint for showing live the protests of the last days, > erupted following the detention of the mayor of Istanbul, Ekrem Imamoglu. RTUK fined and sanctioned HalkTv, Tele1, NowTv (Fox ndr) and Sozcu TV. The latter may not transmit for ten days, while HalkTv and Tele1 have undergone the blocking of an information program for 5 editions.
Among the reasons given by RTUK to justify sanctions is the transmission of protests and speech by the opposition secretary Ozgur Ozel, who asked for the boycott of companies, malls and brands held close to the Turkish government. Images and appeals considered provocatives and dividers as well as an incitement to violence. At the same time, sanctioned broadcasters are accused of having conveyed messages that incite social hatred, but also insults against Turkish President Recep Tayip Erdogan and other government charges.&nbsp;
<h2> Performed and expelled a Bbc correspondent in Istanbul</h2>
The correspondent of Bbc Mark Lowen was expelled from Turkey after being arrested in Istanbul on Wednesday. Lowen has been in Turkey for several days to cover protests against President Recep Tayyip Erdogan, triggered by the arrest of the mayor of Istanbul Ekrem Imamoglu last week. Imamoglu, held on the charge of corruption he denies, is considered the main political rival of Erdogan. He was chosen by his party as a presidential candidate for the 2028 elections.
"This morning (March 27) the Turkish authorities expelled from Istanbul the correspondent of Bbc News Mark Lowen, after taking him from his hotel the day before and holding him for 17 hours. This morning he was given a written notification on his expulsion because he 'represents a threat to the public order'", explained the Bbc in a note. "Being held and deported by the country where I lived for five years and for which I have such a great affection was extremely distressing," Lowen said. "The freedom of press and impartial information are fundamental to any democracy," added the journalist who was also corresponding to Italy. Deborah Turness, CEO of Bbc, added: "This is an extremely worrying accident and we will resort to the Turkish authorities."
<h2> The photographer of the Afp stopped during demonstrations</h2>
AFP photojournalist Yasin Akgul was released, arrested on Monday while documenting the country's major protests. Your lawyer made it known. The 35-year-old reporter is one of seven Turkish journalists arrested this week during massive protests initiated with the arrest, on March 19, of the mayor of Istanbul Ekrem Imamoglu, chief political rival of President Recep Tayyip Erdogan.
Yesterday the agency France Presse had appealed to the Turkish authorities for the liberation of Akgul. In a video, the CEO, Fabrice Fries, underlined that Akgul "was not taking part in the demonstrations, but was covering them as a photographer." There are 190 photos that prove it, he explained. "This arrest has no precedent in Turkey," said Fries, "as far as we know, journalism is not yet illegal in Turkey. So I appeal to Yasin's immediate release."&nbsp;
<h2> EU condemns arrests by journalists, "respect freedoms"</h2>
The European Union "condemnates" arrests of journalists in Turkey and asks the country to "respect the freedom of media, in accordance with European values". "It is essential that journalists can carry out their work without being threatened by violence, harassment or intimidation, to ensure access to all information," said a spokesman of the European Commission.&nbsp;

